Layer 7: The Application Layer
This is the only layer the user actually touches. It provides network services directly to software applications.

The Job: Identifying communication partners, determining resource availability, and synchronizing communication.

Key Protocols: HTTP/HTTPS (Web), DNS (Names), SMTP/IMAP (Email), SSH (Secure Shell).

Cybersecurity Angle: This is where SQL Injection, Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), and DDoS attacks like "HTTP Floods" happen. Security experts use Web Application Firewalls (WAF) to protect this layer.

Layer 6: The Presentation Layer
This is the "Translator" or the "Formatting" layer. It ensures that the data sent from the application layer of one system can be read by the application layer of another.

The Job: Data representation, Encryption/Decryption, and Compression.

Example: When you send a photo, Layer 6 ensures it is encoded as a JPEG. When you use HTTPS, Layer 6 (along with Layer 5) handles the SSL/TLS encryption that keeps your data private.

Cybersecurity Angle: Attackers can exploit vulnerabilities in how data is "unpacked" or decrypted (e.g., malformed SSL certificates).

Layer 5: The Session Layer
This layer manages the "dialogue" between computers. It starts, maintains, and ends the connection (the session).

The Job: Session setup, teardown, and synchronization (checkpoints).

Example: If you are downloading a 2GB file and your connection drops, the Session layer manages the "checkpoint" so you don't have to start the download from zero.

Cybersecurity Angle: Session Hijacking. If an attacker steals your "Session ID" (often stored in a browser cookie), they can pretend to be you without needing your password.

Layer 4: The Transport Layer
This is the first layer where data is actually "moved" reliably.

The Job: Segmentation (chopping data into pieces), Flow Control (not sending data faster than the receiver can handle), and Error Correction.

Key Protocols: TCP (Reliable/Connection-oriented) and UDP (Fast/Connectionless).

The Identifier: Ports (like Port 80, 443, or your random WhatsApp source ports).

Cybersecurity Angle: Port Scanning. Attackers use tools like Nmap to see which "doors" (ports) are open at this layer.

Layer 3: The Network Layer
This is the "Postal Service" of the internet. It handles the routing of data across different networks.

The Job: Logical addressing (IP Addresses) and Path Determination (Routing).

The Hardware: Routers live here.

Key Protocols: IPv4, IPv6, ICMP (Ping), and IGMP.

Cybersecurity Angle: IP Spoofing and DDoS. Attackers hide their identity by faking the Source IP in the packet header at this layer.

Layer 2: The Data Link Layer
This layer handles communication between two devices on the same physical segment (like your phone and your router).

The Job: Physical addressing (MAC Addresses) and error detection at the frame level.

The Hardware: Switches live here.

Sub-layers: 1.  LLC (Logical Link Control): Identifies network protocols.
2.  MAC (Media Access Control): Handles hardware IDs.

Cybersecurity Angle: ARP Spoofing. Since this layer trusts MAC addresses, an attacker can trick a switch into sending them your data.

Layer 1: 
The Physical LayerThe "Basement." This is the actual hardware that moves raw bits ($1$s and $0$s).

The Job: Transmission of raw bitstreams over a physical medium.The Medium: Ethernet cables, Fiber optics, Radio waves (Wi-Fi), Hubs, and Repeaters.




Cybersecurity Angle: Physical Security. If an attacker can plug a "Rubber Ducky" (a malicious USB) into your computer or tap into a physical fiber line, layers 2 through 7 don't matter—you're already hacked.
